<H1>Michelson Interferometer for Passive Atmospheric Sounding (MIPAS)</H1>
</center>
<HR>
The Michelson Interferometer for Passive Atmospheric Sounding 
is one of the core experiments on ESA's <A
href=http://envisat.esa.int/>Envisat</a> satellite, launched on 1st 
March 2002.
MIPAS measures atmospheric limb emission spectra from 685-2410 cm-1
(14.5 to 4.1um) over an altitude range 6-68 km.  After suitable ground processing, these spectra  allow quantification of concentration
      profiles of numerous atmospheric trace species.  In addition, atmospheric temperature as
      well as the distribution of aerosol particles, tropospheric cirrus, and stratospheric ice
      clouds (including polar stratospheric clouds) can also be derived from MIPAS data.
<P>
The objectives of MIPAS are: 
<ul>
      <li>Measurements of geophysical
        parameters in the middle atmosphere; <br>
        <it>Stratospheric chemistry: </it>O<sub>3</sub>, H<sub>2</sub>O, CH<sub>4</sub>, N<sub>2</sub>O,NO<sub>2</sub>,
        and HNO<sub>3</sub>; and<br>
        <it>Climatology: </it>Temperature, CH<sub>4</sub>, N<sub>2</sub>O, O<sub>3</sub> ;
      <li>Study of chemical composition, dynamics, and
        radiation budget of the middle atmosphere;
      <li>Monitoring of stratospheric O<sub>3</sub> and
        CFCs. 
</ul>
<P>
As a unique feature of MIPAS, the  atmospheric parameters
    are determined: 
<ul>
      <li>simultaneously as colocated profiles
      <li>with complete global coverage     
      <li>during day- and nighttime conditions (allowing observations of the
        diurnal variation of trace species), and 
      <li>throughout its mission duration of four years.
</ul>
<P>
<DIV STYLE="border-style:solid; border-width:thin; margin:1cm; padding:10px">
<H3><font color=red><B>MIPAS Data: current status and coverage</B></font></h3>
<DL>
<DT><font color=red><B>Jul02-Mar04: FR17</B></FONT> 
<DD> MIPAS operated at full spectral resolution (0.025cm<sup>-1</sup>)
with a nominal 17 step scan pattern, giving 3km steps in
the lower atmosphere (now known as "FR17" mode). 
ESA have processed all these data to L2. Coverage
maps for this period
can be found on <a href=http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk/group/mipas/L2/>"MIPAS L2
Profile Maps"</a>

<DT><font color=red><B>Aug04-Sep04: RR17 </B> </FONT>
<DD> MIPAS operated at reduced spectral resolution (0.0625cm<sup>-1</sup>) 
but keeping the original scan pattern (3km steps). 
ESA have recently  processed this data to L2 and
is included in the  <a href=http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk/group/mipas/L2/>"MIPAS L2
Profile Maps"</a>.

<DT><font color=red><B>Jan05-present: RR27</B> </FONT>
<DD>Still at reduced spectral resolution but with a nominal scan pattern
consisting of 27 steps with 1.5km spacing in the lower atmosphere. 
In practice, a significant amount of time is also spent in "UTLS1" mode,
similar to the new nominal mode but with 19 steps, removing the higher 
tangent altitudes. The instrument now operates on a 35% duty cycle
rather than continuously.
<UL>
<LI> ESA are currently processing the data only up to L1B (ie spectra).
The data released so far are shown on the
<a href=http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk/group/mipas/L1BRR/>"Reduced Resolution
L1B coverage maps"</a>.
<LI> If no L1B data is currently shown for a particular period, it may be
that it just hasn't been processed yet.
Check the MIPAS Mission Planning Documents 
(<a href=./meetings/MIPAS_Mission_Planning_2005.html>2005</a>,
<a href=./meetings/MIPAS_Mission_Planning_2006_DRAFT.html>2006</a>)
to see if any observations were planned.
<LI> ESA L2 for this mode is not expected until towards the end of 2006 but
if you're in a hurry we can run our own Oxford retrieval scheme on
small amounts of data. 
</UL>
</DL>
06JUL06 Anu Dudhia ( <A
href=mailto:dudhia@atm.ox.ac.uk>dudhia@atm.ox.ac.uk</a> ).

</DIV>
